**Stale Job replacement may transiently fail in real Kubernetes due to finalizers**

After `c.Delete(ctx, existing)` the old Job may not be immediately removed if the Kubernetes Jobs controller has set the `batch.kubernetes.io/job-tracking` finalizer (stable since Kubernetes 1.27). In that case `Delete` only sets a `deletionTimestamp`; the object remains in the API server until the finalizer is cleared. The immediately-following `c.Create(ctx, job)` with the same name will then fail with `AlreadyExists`.

The fake client used in tests deletes synchronously, so all tests pass, but production reconcilers will log a spurious `creating replacement Job` error and requeue until the finalizer is released.

The cleanest fix is to treat `AlreadyExists` on the replacement `Create` as a transient condition:

```go
if err := c.Create(ctx, job); err != nil {
    if apierrors.IsAlreadyExists(err) {
        // Old Job still terminating; wait for the next reconcile.
        return false, nil
    }
    return false, fmt.Errorf("creating replacement Job %s/%s: %w", job.Namespace, job.Name, err)
}
```

